{
  "text": "Molecular models of rhodopsin based upon electron density projection maps that were constructed before the Wrst Fig. 1 The most striking diVerence between the crystal structures of rhodopsin (PDBid 1f88, [CITATION_1] ) and the beta-2 adrenergic receptor (PDBid 2rh1, [CITATION_2] ) concerns the structure and location of the extracellular loop between helix IV and V. The loop IV-V in rhodopsin forms a -sheet that folds into the binding pocket (yellow), whereas loop IV-V in the beta-2 adrenergic receptor forms an -helix and extends towards the extracellular environment (purple) crystal structure became available proposed a speciWc interaction between transmembrane (TM) helices III and V, which appeared to be mediated by amino acid residues Glu122 and His211 on TM helices III and V, respectively. [CITATION_3] used a combination of site-directed mutagenesis and Fourier-transform infrared spectroscopy (FTIR) to validate this hypothesis.",
  "correct_citation": {
